	<div id="panel">Given a polygon on the map, calculate and display population and housing counts based on 2010 U.S. Census Blocks.</br></br>Tools / Components</br>Ruby - Rails - JS - Route360 - Google Maps API - PostgreSQL/PostGIS - 2010 USA Census Data</br></br>By clicking on the map with the marker tool (upper left), a 3 minute isochrone (drive-time) polygon is calculated using Route360 REST Services and is subsequently inserted into a PostgreSQL/PostGIS table.  The polygon is then buffered and used to do a spatial query in PostgreSQL to determine intersection of the buffered polygon against census block data.</br></br>Uniform distribution of population and housing counts are assumed within a census block.</br></br>The buffered polygon is then displayed on the map.  Within the buffered polygon is displayed the original Route360 returned isochrone polygon and line work.</br> (cool stuff, check them out... www.route360.com)</br></br>PostgreSQL is hosted on a Raspberry Pi 2 board running Raspbian 8 (Jessie).  The Census Block table in the database contains over 11 millions records covering the entire United States.</br></br>This website is still a work in progress.  There are known issues that will be addressed, maybe some enhancements.  This webpage is for demonstration purposes.</br></br>https://github.com/greghorne/mappy</div>
	
